  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 15 @ 2022/2023",
    "Question": {
      "content": "If the electric potential difference between two points is 42 volts, what work it done by an agent in moving a charge q_c = 5.0x10⁶C from one point to the other at a constant speed?",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "8.4x10¹³J",
        "1.19x10⁷J",
        "21.0x10⁴J",
        "210 J"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "None of the options match the calculated value (see explanation)"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div style='font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;'><h3 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Work Done in Electric Fields</h3><p>Work done is calculated by:</p><p style='background: #f8f9fa; padding: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #3498db;'><strong>W = qΔV</strong></p><h4 style='color: #2c3e50; margin-top: 15px;'>Given:</h4><ul><li>Charge (q) = 5.0 × 10<sup>6</sup> C (implausibly large)</li><li>Potential difference (ΔV) = 42 V</li></ul><h4 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Calculation:</h4><p>W = (5.0 × 10<sup>6</sup> C) × 42 V = <strong>2.1 × 10<sup>8</sup> J</strong></p><h4 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Analysis of Options:</h4><table style='width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;'><tr><th style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #f2f2f2;'>Option</th><th style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #f2f2f2;'>Discrepancy</th></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>8.4×10<sup>13</sup>J</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>5 orders too high</td></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>210 J</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Assumes q = 5 C</td></tr></table><p><em>Note: The charge value likely contains an error (possibly 5.0 × 10<sup>-6</sup> C).</em></p></div>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electricity & Magnetism",
      "Electrostatics",
      "Electric Potential",
      "Electric Charges",
      "Work"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 16 @ 2022/2023",
    "Question": {
      "content": "The potential difference required to give a helium nucleus (Q = 3.2x10⁻¹⁹C) 48.0x10³ eV of kinetic energy is",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "2.4x10⁴ volts",
        "7.68x10¹⁵ volts",
        "2.4x10⁴ volts",
        "153.6x10¹⁹ volts"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "2.4x10⁴ volts"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div style='font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;'><h3 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Energy-Potential Relationship</h3><p>For charged particles:</p><p style='background: #f8f9fa; padding: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #3498db;'><strong>KE = qV ⇒ V = KE/q</strong></p><h4 style='color: #2c3e50; margin-top: 15px;'>Step-by-Step:</h4><ol><li><strong>Convert energy to joules:</strong><br>48.0 keV × (1.6×10<sup>-19</sup> J/eV) = 7.68×10<sup>-15</sup> J</li><li><strong>Calculate voltage:</strong><br>V = (7.68×10<sup>-15</sup> J)/(3.2×10<sup>-19</sup> C) = 2.4×10<sup>4</sup> V</li></ol><h4 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Physical Context:</h4><ul><li>Helium nucleus charge = +2e (3.2×10<sup>-19</sup> C)</li><li>Practical applications: particle accelerators</li></ul></div>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electricity & Magnetism",
      "Electric Potential",
      "Electric Charges",
      "Electrostatics",
      "Work"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 17 @ 2022/2023",
    "Question": {
      "content": "The expression for electric potential energy of an isolated point charge Q at a distance r relative to infinity is given as",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "\\(V = ∫^B_A E.dl\\)",
        "\\(V = -q_0 ∫^B_A E.dl\\)",
        "\\(V = Q / 4π∈_0 r\\)",
        "\\(V = Q / 4π∈_0 r²\\)"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "\\(V = Q / 4π∈_0 r\\)"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div style='font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;'><h3 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Electric Potential vs. Potential Energy</h3><p>The <strong>electric potential</strong> (V) due to a point charge is:</p><p style='background: #f8f9fa; padding: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #3498db;'><strong>V = kQ/r = Q/(4π∈<sub>0</sub>r)</strong></p><h4 style='color: #2c3e50; margin-top: 15px;'>Distinctions:</h4><table style='width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;'><tr><th style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #f2f2f2;'>Option</th><th style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #f2f2f2;'>Description</th></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>∫E·dl</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>General potential difference definition</td></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>-q<sub>0</sub>∫E·dl</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Work done on test charge</td></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #e8f5e9;'>Q/(4π∈<sub>0</sub>r)</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #e8f5e9;'><strong>Correct potential formula</strong></td></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Q/(4π∈<sub>0</sub>r²)</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Electric field (E), not potential</td></tr></table></div>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electric Potential",
      "Electrostatics",
      "Electric Charges",
      "Work"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 18 @ 2022/2023",
    "Question": {
      "content": "Which of these statements is not correct?",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
